(1)
Central Park: The Sailboat Pool, on the east side of the Park, showing Fifth Avenue from 74th to 81st Streets, and the Metropolitan Museum of art at the extreme left. The large-domed building in the center is Temple Beth-El ("House of God"), on the S.E. corner of 70th Street. The ecclesiastical looking spire a block north of it is part of Senator Clark's mansion
(William A. Clark of Montana).
Summer, 124.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
The same, early the following spring. Notice the new apartment
buildings in the block from 76th to 77th Streets.
Both of these views were taken from Pilgrim Hill, the little slope
north of the 72nd Street drive.
March, 1925.
P. L. Sperr.

(1)
Central Park: Sailboat Pool; the view is east, with Fifth Avenue
from 74th to 75th Streets in the background.
May 17, 1933.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
The same, but With-the view northeast, so that the Carlyle, a tall apartment building at Madison Avenue and 76th Street, is seen behind the Fifth Avenue block from 74th to 75th Streets.
May 17, 1933.
P. L. Sperr.
(3)
Fifth Avenue from 75th to 77th Streets. The tall building in the right background is the Carlyle apartment house at Madison Avenue and 70th Street. The synagogue on the S.E. corner of Fifth Avenue and 70th Street is Temple Beth-El. The apartment
building on and adjoining the N.W. corner of 77th Street includes the site of Senator Clark's mansion, demolished in 1927.  May 17, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.
